Defining Functions

# Define function for plotting QQ-plots (ggpubr) and histograms (ggplot2) of DIFFERENCES
func.qqhisto.analyte <- function(x) {
  histo <- ggplot(
    df.cytokines.wide[df.cytokines.wide$analyte == x,],
    aes(x = difference)) +
    geom_histogram(breaks = hist(
      df.cytokines.wide$difference[df.cytokines.wide$analyte == x],
      plot = F)$breaks) +
    labs(title = paste0("Histogram of ", x)) +
    theme_gray()
  qq <- ggqqplot(
    df.cytokines.wide$difference[df.cytokines.wide$analyte == x],
    main = paste0("QQ-plot of ", x),
    ggtheme = theme_grey())
  plot_grid(histo, qq)
}

# Define function to identify outliers in dataset "df.cytokines.wide"
# Outliers are based upon differences between baseline and day 5.
func.outlier.analyte <- function(x) {
df.cytokines.wide %>%
  filter(
    analyte == x) %>% 
  identify_outliers(difference)
}

# Define function for boxplots
func.boxplot.analyte <- function(x) {
  df.cytokines.long %>% 
    filter(analyte == x) %>% 
    ggboxplot(
      data = .,
      x = "visit_type",
      y = "value",
      main = x,
      xlab = "Visit",
      ylab = paste0("Value of ", x),
      add = "jitter",
      ggtheme = theme_grey()
    )
}

# Define loop function for batch processing
# "cytokine" = unique variable
# "x" = a list, for which the function will loop through
func.boxplots <- function(x) {
  for (cytokine in x) { 
    boxplot(cytokine ~ visit_type,
            data = df.cytokines,
            xlab = "Visit")
  }
}

# Define function for t-testing
func.ttest.panel <- function(x) {
  df.cytokines.long %>% filter(
    panel == x) %>% 
    group_by(analyte) %>% 
    t_test(value ~ visit_type, paired = TRUE, detailed = TRUE)
}

Clearly, many outliers exist. Lets quantify the outliers.

Outliers

Outliers and extreme outliers are defined as follows:

Values above Q3 + 1.5xIQR or below Q1 - 1.5xIQR are considered as outliers. Values above Q3 + 3xIQR or below Q1 - 3xIQR are considered as extreme points (or extreme outliers).

# Check for  outliers
df.outliers.proinflammatory <- df.proinflammatory.wide %>%
  filter(analyte %in% notnormal.proinflammatory) %>% 
  group_by(analyte) %>% 
  identify_outliers(difference)

df.extremeouts.proinflammatory <- df.proinflammatory.wide %>%

Statistical Evaluation of Differences

For Data of Normal Distribution

We will use a paired T-test to evaluate differences. Assumptions are

  1. Data of normal distribution (true)
  2. No extreme outliers (not yet evaluated)

For Data of NOT-normal Distribution

We can use Wilcoxon Signed Rank test to check for statistical differences. The assumption that the differences are symetrically distributed .

# Wilcoxon signed rank test on paired samples 
# For non-normal distributed analytes we will perform a Wilcoxon signed rank test
df.proinflammatory.NOEXTREMESv1.wide %>%
  filter(baseline != "NA" & day_5 != "NA") %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(baseline, day_5),
    names_to = "visit_type",
    values_drop_na = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(analyte %in% notnormal.proinflammatory.NOEXTREMESv1) %>% 
  group_by(analyte) %>% 
  wilcox_test(value ~ visit_type, paired = TRUE, detailed = TRUE) %>%
  add_significance() %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), round, 2))
